[h1]Note:[/h1]
For full disclosure, I have never played any of the Panzer General titles (which seems to be the point of comparison for most players). Instead I will review this game based on its own merits.

[quote]The key was provided for review purposes[/quote]

[h1]TL;DR? See Conclusion[/h1]

[h1]INTRODUCTION:[/h1]

Panzer Corps is a 2011 turn-based strategy game (TBS) developed by Flashback Games and The Lordz Games Studio with Slitherine Ltd. as the publisher. It features a hex-based gameplay mechanic, dynamic and branching single player campaign with a very unique unit veterancy system.

[h1]PLOT (No Spoilers):[/h1]

Take command of the Wehrmacht and lead the fatherland to ultimate victory. You may also play as the Allied (DLC) powers in their defense of the free world, or may be play as the Soviet Union (DLC) and fight for the glorious motherland. If you’re like me however, play as the world-renowned Afrika Korps (DLC) and kick the Allies out of Africa.  

[h1]PROS:[/h1]
+ Quick and easy to learn game mechanics;
+ Graphics and art style is well suited for the game style (I personally would have liked an option to use unit counters rather than the static sprites);
+ Custom difficulty options (make it as easy or difficult as you want);
+ Land, air and sea combat with combined arms elements;
+ Extensive unit variety, with the ability to either upgrade or downgrade the unit to a different unit type to suit your needs. (can only be done during the deployment stage or if the unit is in a city);
+ Unique unit veterancy system which includes heroes, medals and battle history (I like this feature because it adds to my immersive experience with the game);
+ Unit Library (similar to Shogun 2 Total War’s Encyclopedia where you can learn more about your favorite unit’s real world history.);
+ Simple but easy to understand user interface with the appropriate tool tips to show what the button does;
+ Good background music;
+ Branching campaign (the outcome of your battles will have an impact on the overall story);
+ Good replay value because of the branching campaign feature.

[h1]CONS:[/h1]
- The overall map feels small (or may be the hexes are just too big) which leads to relatively quick scenarios;
- AI’s decision making skills are questionable;
- Limited scenario options if you only buy the base game…(see next CON);
- Because most of the other scenarios are sold as DLC;
- No unit supply chains (meaning you can fully reinforce or resupply them directly in front of enemy units. It would have been better if they implemented a mechanic where reinforcing or resupplying near an enemy unit is not as effective as reinforcing them away from the front lines.)
- No option to use unit counters instead of static sprites.

[h1]NEUTRAL:[/h1]
+/- Voice acting (specially for the Wehrmacht narrator) could be better;
+/- So-so sound design.

[h1]CONCLUSION:[/h1]
Panzer Corps is a [b]GREAT GAME[/b] and I [b]highly RECOMMEND[/b] this for World War II turn-base strategy fans. It is a very good hex-based strategy game that has strategic and tactical depth with enough complexity to have you wanting more (unfortunately, sold as DLC).

[h1]WORTH IT?[/h1]
The base game is $19.99 (or your regional equivalent) while the bundle with all the DLCs is $79.62. Though I do like the game and recommend it, if you’re on a budget, it may be worthwhile to wait for a Steam sale and get the entire package rather than purchasing the content piecemeal.

[h1]FINAL NOTES:[/h1]
Like I said, I have never played any of the Panzer General titles so I can’t make a valid comparison. If you have played Order of Battle: Pacific / World War II and liked it however, then I’m pretty confident in saying that you’ll like Panzer Corps too.
